    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and im kinda confused. i feel like i'm paying a lot every month but the actual amount i owe isnt going down as much as i thought it would. can u explain how the interest actually works with the payments? why does it seem like so much of my money is just disappearing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the student loan statement, a tricky beast indeed! It's like trying to catch a slippery, sneaky goblin in the dark. You make your monthly payments, right? But here's the catch: a chunk of your payment goes to the principal (that's the actual amount you owe), and a chunk goes to interest (the goblin's sneaky tax). The interest is calculated on the remaining balance, so as you make payments, the interest keeps growing on the remaining principal. It's like the goblin keeps multiplying, making it seem like you're paying more and more, but actually, you're just chasing the goblin around. The principal only starts to shrink once you've paid off the interest. So, it's like you're trying to catch the goblin, but it's always one step ahead, always multiplying, always growing. That's why it feels like your money is disappearing into the goblin's lair. But don't worry, with time and patience, you'll finally catch that goblin and put an end to it!",
